Here's an example to illustrate the difference:
```java
String s1 = new String("hello");
String s2 = new String("hello");

if (s1 == s2) {  // This will return false because they are different objects in memory
    System.out.println("s1 and s2 refer to the same object");
}

if (s1.equals(s2)) {  // This will return true because they have the same characters in the same order
    System.out.println("s1 and s2 have the same content");
}
```

In general, you should use the `.equals()` method to compare strings in Java. This is because strings in Java are immutable objects, meaning that once they are created, their contents cannot be changed. Therefore, two strings with the same characters in the same order should be considered equal, regardless of whether they are the same object in memory or not.

